snippet.textDisplay: My good friend in Konárovice, Czech Republic had a John Deere dealership there from 1994 to 2015, finally forced out of business not by competition, but by John Deere itself. They put more and more screws on him until Deere finally said he'd have to get a humongous tractor all the way from a village in the middle of the country to Hamburg, Germany for huge repair bills when it could be done locally for pennies on the dollar. He was in tears when we spoke of it, it was his life's work, because instead of selling simple, reliable tractors he was forced to push the latest thing, with the goddamn climate change friendly Greta Thunburg approved exhaust systems, the lazer guided wheels and bullshit like that that nobody can fix or even tweak, and he wasn't allowed to sell older, more reliable tractors second hand. Remember your first car? I do, a 1979 Fiat Strada, a fuckin' engineering disaster but I could fix that piece of shit with my Swiss army knife, random tools lying around the high school shop class and a bit of guesswork, and I'm a so-so mechanic, but I could do it to it with confidence. Cars these days? My dad bought a VW Jetta a couple of years ago, I looked under the hood, it was like a Ghostbusters proton pack, fuckin' forget working on that thing.

snippet.textDisplay: Okay I have played a part on both ends of this. For starters it is not nearly as bad as they are leading it on to be. Typically if the tractor throws a code you can call into service and they are going to tell you what is going on. 95% of the time the farmer can do the job themselves but they choose not to because the job will be done faster and likely better by a trained tech. Second of all these machines are incredibly complex and if you start just handing EST's to farmers at some point the farmer will likely brick the tractor and then it wont even be able to be put in gear. It is not like your handing over microsoft word, you can go in and change very large meaningful parameters, make a combine think its a 70 hp tractor. It can get messy very fast. There are tons of things that take a lot of schooling and training  to be able to understand what is going on so even if it was handed out it would be impossible without training for them to understand what to do. On the farming side of it i would say the majority of stuff we fixed ourselves except things like emissions stuff. There where very few occurrences when we had no choice but to have the dealership come out. While crop prices have stunk there is no reason to be taking frustration out on the dealers because we do our absolute best ot help the customer and give breaks when we truly feel it is deserving.

If you watch the debates in state legislatures about right to repair bills, it’s just sad to watch. The bills are always presented in the most logical and common sense way possible, while representatives from the big companies give bullshit nonanswers to simple yes or no questions and refuse to answer concerns of lawmakers and instead offer to “meet and have a discussion about it later” (which obviously means to meet and bribe them later).

It’s so extremely obvious what the outcome should be, yet thanks to weak-willed assholes on both sides of the isle in these state governments getting paid off by the lobbyists, the bills get voted down every time.

Watching this is like watching someone argue the sky is blue by pointing up to the blue sky, and then a lobbyist argues that the sky is green, slips the lawmakers a couple bucks, and then they all agree that it is green. It’s embarrassing.

snippet.textDisplay:
No. Your John Deere tractor isn't going to be around in 10 years. It may still be there. But it's a damn good guarantee, that some sensor, somewhere is going to render that tool useless. And then they will make that sensor, obsolete. It's called planned obsolescence. And they plan on making your vehicle obsolete. Because, they are now in the business of selling financing. They don't care what product you get. As long as you are financing it over the course of the next seven to ten years. And 20 years from now, you're going to be cutting that thing up with a torch, and sending it to the scrap yards. Because Iron and Steel is forever. Technology, is forever changing.

And by the time you're done cutting it up, and sending it to the scrap yard oh, you will find out what the true value of that machine is. Because if it isn't running, and it isn't driving, it's scrap.

snippet.textDisplay:
My first car was an 83 Cadillac Coupe DeVille. If I held down the on and heat button at the same time. The car would do a self diagnostics, going down the road. It was incredible. One of the most amazing things I've ever seen as a repair technician. But that technology was soon removed from the cars, and replaced with a data Communications port. Giving the dealership the diagnostic computer, meant $100 an hour, for diagnostics at a Cadillac dealership. One of the ways I found to hack that vehicle, was, everything under the Cadillac emblem, was an Oldsmobile. So replacing the expensive Cadillac parts with cheaper Oldsmobile parts, was a great way to save a lot of money. Now I've watched, from a technician perspective over the years. As the tech companies have deliberately sabotage everything from automobiles to tractors. Specifically so they can stick little sensors in little tiny orifices. That's giving the country of California, the fifth largest economy in the world. Which is now 7th... but one fact will never change. It's been true since Henry Ford drove his first quadricycle out of the shed. It will never change. And that is, Spark, fuel, compression ... everything else is bullshit.
And if you're going to put your b******, in my car, and then make me deal with your b****** to get my car fixed. You can have the car back. You can have the tractor back. You can take your little diode resistors... And stick them in your orifice. Don't care which one... You choose.

We were warned in the 80s, that technology was going to be used to suppress industry. We were warned. And here it is. Doing exactly what they warned us they were going to do with it. The main reason why apple is involved. Is because they don't want you people opening up their laptops, and finding out that they're really crap. Their garbage. Their garbage, cost you a thousand bucks a throw. They know it's garbage. They have known its garbage. Yet, they don't want us to figure out, they are producing garbage. Opening up their computers, will definitely show the world, what kind of garbage they are creating.

snippet.textDisplay: In order for "Right to Repair" to succeed, and I'm all for it, Apple would have to be disbanded.  They have been at the forefront of proprietary technology since the 1980's.   My prominent Mechanic friend who's shop mostly works on AMG's BMW Porches and Audi's had a customer with a Lamborghini Gallardo, which shares the same V10 as the Audi R8.  The Audi Injector is priced at $165 each and well stocked at the dealership, as well as being available aftermarket.  The Lamborghini injector differs only in the little bull stamp on the stem.  Part number is the same, Terminal is the same.  The price?  $1,400 per injector and availability, only at the dealer, has a 3 month back order.  :/  The customer actually went for the originals in his Gallardo, paying over $18,000 for the repair, because he's loaded and doesn't care.  But just goes to show what Gremlins "Right to Repair" might unearth.  Also why many manufactures are preferring to block access to their technologies.
